post_text: Thomas Jefferson School - Ana Flores, TJS pre-k teacher, started a free Union City Community Fridge. She took this initiative because, during the school closure time, she was assisting some of the families in her classroom who relied on the district’s meal program and yet continued to be food insecure. The mission of the UC Community Fridge is to provide food support for our diverse community. The Community Fridge is open 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, and located at 709 15th Street. Congratulations, Ana, we're so proud of you!

post_text:
Emerson Century 21st CCLC Virtual!

1. With Ms. Glass, students are doing the "Plot Diagram Dance.” We reviewed the elements of a fiction text with a song and dance and performed it together!

2. The third video is of period 1 students reading and discussing notes on Edmentum about how to do a close reading of a fiction text.

3. Ms. Glass's students in Emerson are on roll. The video is of online period 2 students presenting their virtual blueprints for their new and improved Emerson Middle School cafeteria. After they presented their ideas, we talked about the pros/cons of each model, and then students revised their work, based on their peers’ feedback.

Dear Jefferson Jaguars,
Thank you for an interesting, challenging, and productive school year. We can’t thank you enough for the endless hours in doing whatever was necessary to support our students and families. We don't know what the future holds, but until next school year...we are wishing you love, laughter, rest, and health.

Stay safe, everyone,
The JTS Administrative Team - Mike, Laurie, Ana and Marianne

post_text: UNION CITY EDUCATION ASSOCIATION—PRIDE COVID-19 INITIATIVE. Our next event was providing food to a local homeless shelter, PERC (Palisade Emergency Residence Corporation). Director Carol Mori said that on weekends, they do not a have to cook, and it only made sense to help out on a weekend. We reached out to a local cafeteria, “Juana and Gloria.” They prepared trays of rice and beans, chicken, pork, tres leches cake, and flan. We also went to our dependable merchant, Gino, at La Bella and asked for pasta and salad. It was the Saturday of Memorial Day weekend, and it was raining heavily most of the day. Mr. Pressey and I had to pick up and deliver. Good deeds go rewarded, as each and every time we had to load and unload my SUV the rain stopped. What turned out to be for approximately 165 people, turned into enough (as per one PERC staffer) to be enough food to last until Monday. What was to be several trays of hot food turned into a feast of 3 carloads, with rains ceasing to load and unload, truly amazing.

UNION CITY EDUCATION ASSOCIATION
PRIDE – COVID-19 INTIATIVE recognized our Emergency Medical Service, EMTs. Upon speaking with the supervisor George Fierro, we wanted all his staff to be acknowledged, so we reached out to Gino from La Bella. He prepared hot pasta, meatballs, vegetables, salad, cookies, beverages, and with any extra money, he made platters of sandwiches. Coincidently, the day the meals were delivered was also EMS Day.

post_text:
In Emerson, Ms. Glass's 210 class is still producing outstanding tech integrated work.

We would like to share Zuri Miler’s 210 work.
The assignment was: Create a presentation on mindset using what you've learned about fixed and growth mindset, as well as, the research on history’s most famous failures.
Please make sure you focus on the following:
How did these people fail?
How did they come back even stronger to accomplish their goals?
How do you relate to what you have researched?
What kind of mindset do you think you have?
What steps can you take to change your mindset?

post_text:
UHMS congratulates Mrs. Michelle Popailo for being this week's Teacher of the Week! Let's get to know a little about Mrs. Popailo!

1. Where did you grow up? I was born in Washington Heights, NY. I moved to West New York, NJ, when I was in the 6th grade.

2. Where did you go to school? I graduated from Memorial High School in West New York. I received my teaching and graduate degrees from New Jersey City University.

3. What is one thing students don't know about you that would surprise them? When I was in the 4th grade, I used to play the trumpet!

4. What is a talent/hobby/collection you spend time on outside of school hours? I LOVE to read & exercise.

5. What is your favorite thing about teaching? My favorite thing about teaching is watching my classroom of students and adults become a real family every year!

Congratulations Mrs. Popailo! Thank you for everything you do! Keep up the great work! #UHMSTogetherAtHome

post_text: Union Hill Middle School would like to congratulate the Students of the Week for the week of June 1, Sarela Roque and Lizzie Lauzardo! Sarela has shown amazing adaptability during virtual school. She is working diligently in all of her classes. She is always present and participates with enthusiasm. Additionally, she is a good role model for her peers during lessons and discussions on Zoom. Lizzie is an exemplary student. During the year she was quiet, but dedicated. Ironically, VS has given her a voice to communicate outstanding work and ideas. Not only does she demonstrate outstanding work, but her dedication of mindfulness and attendance on Zoom is always full of positivity for her peers. Great work, ladies! We are so proud of you! Both girls received pizza dinners from Terminis. #UHMSTogetherAtHome

post_text:
This year has been an exciting and creative year for all of our young artists at Colin Powell School. Despite the unforeseen challenges this academic year, our students continued their creativity in a virtual art class! This change has exhibited a remarkable way to communicate creativity in any situation. This year, our students were left to create without the luxury of an art room and familiar art supplies, and considering the circumstances, they have done a fantastic job!

"You can't use up creativity. The more you use, the more you have." - Maya Angelou

https://www.artsonia.com/artshow/158944/8096

post_text:
Roosevelt School was honored to host a Virtual Memorial Day Assembly today. In attendance were veterans Lucy Del Gaudio, Earl Granville, Rick Kolberg, Nikki Verneuille, Greg Hacke, Jonathan Lopez, and Christopher Martinez. The veterans joined virtually from all parts of the country, along with Roosevelt 5th & 6th graders, principal Ms. O'Connell, and Roosevelt faculty. They shared many inspirational messages with the students about how to overcome challenges. They were all such meaningful words to hear during this unique moment in history.

Veteran Lucy Del Gaudio challenged the Roosevelt students to take the time to reflect this weekend. Reflect on how to give back to the community, and try to connect. Even if it's a smile, we all need that human connection.

Thank you, veterans, for your service and for taking the time to inspire us today!

post_text:
Congratulations to JMSA Theatre program's production of EURYDICE for taking home the Montclair State University Foxy Award for Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actor in a Classical Play! UCHS's Matthew Melo won the award for his role as Nasty Interesting Man, under the direction of Anthony Gusevich.

The JMSA production of EURYDICE was nominated for seven Foxy Awards this year, which is more nominations than any UCHS or JMSA show has ever been nominated for since UCHS opened.

The Foxy Awards recognizes excellence in the production of high school and middle school straight plays throughout New Jersey.

text:

post_text:
We are honored and proud to have our Eagles Math Scholars represent Emerson in competitions such as the MathCounts State Championship. On Wednesday, May 13, 2020, these two teams competed against many different teams from across the nation in a series of three examination sessions. Round 1 consisted of a team round where team members had to complete a series of problems. They were not given a communication tool, so they had to figure out how to complete the test as a team in 20 minutes. The next two rounds were the individual rounds in which each member had to complete their own problems in a sprint round and a target round.

Congratulations on your HONORABLE MENTIONS!

post_text: Eugenio Maria de Hostos Early Childhood Center wants to take this opportunity to honor our principal, Mrs. Adriana Birne, on National Principal’s Day. As principal, she not only oversees our school in its entirety, but, more importantly, has made a special connection with each and every one of us, and for that we are very thankful. We collaborated as a group to reciprocate our deepest appreciation by choosing an adjective that we each feel describes our principal. Mrs. Birne is an educational leader who puts the needs and concerns of our community first and foremost. At Eugenio Maria de Hostos, we share two things in common: being the best educational leaders possible, and the love and respect we have for our principal, Mrs. Adriana Birne. Thank you for all you do!

post_text:
Currently, New Jersey joins 45 other states that have ordered or recommended schools to remain closed for the rest of the school year.

The Union City Board of Education will continue to provide exceptional education and support our school community. We will continue to reconvene our Emergency Preparedness Task Force to develop plans for social distancing, remote learning, and provide safe, learning environments for all stakeholders.

As we continue to work with Mayor and State Senator Brian P. Stack and city fathers we will continue to provide guidance and policies as they arise in the coming weeks. Please stay safe and thank you for all the wonderful work that is being done.

Silvia Abbato
Superintendent of Schools

My RWS Team,
It was great seeing and speaking with all of you today. How wonderful it was to connect and get updates on your lives and how well you are doing both at home and with your virtual lessons. I am touched that more than 95% of the staff joined the Zoom Social. It is important to maintain our connection through this pandemic. Our next Zoom will be towards the end of next month if we don’t resume our normal daily activity at Robert Waters School. That Zoom Social, I would like to invite your children and/or pets to partake in the Zoom since we don’t get to see your children. It is a perfect way to see how each of our families have grown....
Stay Well and Stay Safe❤
With love always.
Ms Tieri
Principal
